---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Case Study: Trauma-Informed Onboarding | AstroPraxis">
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-b from-black via-gray-900 to-black text-white py-24 px-6 text-center">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4">Designing a Trauma-Informed Onboarding Flow</h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-gray-400">
        How we reimagine orientation and hiring processes as spaces of care — not control.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-black text-white py-20 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto space-y-16 text-base leading-relaxed text-gray-300">

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Why This Matters</h2>
        <p>
          Most onboarding systems are structured to serve policy, not people. They frontload paperwork, obscure expectations, and quietly punish vulnerability.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          For folks with trauma histories, disability, or marginalized identities, these systems reinforce harm. We believe onboarding should be a process of mutual welcome, clarity, and power-sharing.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">A Typical Flow (The Problem)</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-400">
          <li>Intake form with no context or accommodations</li>
          <li>Meeting invites with unclear power dynamics</li>
          <li>Org chart that conceals decision-makers</li>
          <li>“Here’s our handbook” without dialogue or values</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 italic text-sm text-gray-500">Result: Confusion, disempowerment, and a quick return to masking or self-protection.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Our Design Principles</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-400">
          <li><strong>Consent-first:</strong> Don’t assume readiness. Always ask.</li>
          <li><strong>Transparent hierarchy:</strong> Don’t hide power — explain it.</li>
          <li><strong>Predictable pacing:</strong> Provide schedules, roadmaps, and choices.</li>
          <li><strong>Multiple modes:</strong> Let people absorb information how they learn best.</li>
          <li><strong>Ongoing onboarding:</strong> Welcome is a process, not an event.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">A Redesigned Flow (The Alternative)</h2>
        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-indigo-300">Day 0: Welcome Letter</h3>
            <p>A human-first intro email with voice and intention. Links to intro materials with estimated reading times and a note: “There is no rush.”</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-indigo-300">Day 1: Intro Meeting</h3>
            <p>Grounded in purpose and consent. Space for questions. Explicit “what you can expect” outline shared upfront.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-indigo-300">Week 1: Flow with Flexibility</h3>
            <p>Asynchronous intros to team. Access to roles + decision charts. Onboarding buddy, not just a supervisor.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">What You Can Try Today</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-400">
          <li>Give candidates an agenda and expectations before every meeting.</li>
          <li>Make your onboarding docs skimmable and annotatable.</li>
          <li>Ask “What would help you feel welcome?” in your intake process.</li>
          <li>Designate a care point person — not just HR or tech support.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="pt-10 border-t border-gray-700">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 text-center">
          Need help reworking your onboarding for real inclusion? <a href="/contact" class="text-indigo-400 hover:underline">Let’s talk.</a>
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
